    <completed-on>2026-06-26</completed-on>
    <summary>
      Two of three POML edits applied verbatim:
      1. AiSearchOptions.cs:7 — KnowledgeIndexName default `spaarke-knowledge-index-v2` → `spaarke-files-index` ✅
      2. AnalysisOptions.cs:69 — SharedIndexName default `spaarke-knowledge-index-v2` → `spaarke-files-index` ✅
      3. AiSearchOptions.cs:8 — DiscoveryIndexName REMOVE → DEFERRED to task 046 (grep cleanup) per coordination strategy below.

      DEFERRED REMOVAL RATIONALE:
      The POML step 4 ("Build must succeed") + step 5 ("consumers will compile errors") + acceptance criterion #2 ("property no longer exists in source") are internally contradictory — 4 production files (RagService.cs, RagIndexingPipeline.cs, IRagService.cs, KnowledgeBaseEndpoints.cs) and 8 test files reference DiscoveryIndexName. Removing the property here breaks the build between task 030 and the consumer tasks 031-037.

      STRATEGY A (applied):
      - DiscoveryIndexName marked `[Obsolete(...)]` with explicit FR-14 + task-046 cleanup directive
      - Default value updated to canonical `spaarke-files-index` so any remaining reader sees the live index (no production behavior change vs. removal — both stop pointing at the retired `discovery-index`)
      - 5 new CS0618 compiler warnings now flag every consumer site → each task in 031-037 grep-finds its work
      - Property removal lands cleanly in task 046 grep cleanup after consumers are updated

      Per CLAUDE.md §11 "Component Justification — Default to Reuse": this is a deferral, not new surface — DiscoveryIndexName already exists; the change is removing it. The Obsolete attribute is the canonical .NET deprecation path and matches the established Spaarke pattern (`DemoProvisioningOptions.Environments` line 347 uses the same `[Obsolete]` "Will be removed after X migration" idiom).

      Build verification: `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/` → 0 errors, 23 warnings (5 new CS0618 on consumers + 18 pre-existing). No regressions.
    </summary>
